---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Key Concepts of Advaita Vedanta">
  <main class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <header class="mb-12 text-center">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-3">
        Key Concepts of Advaita Vedanta
      </h1>
      <p class="text-text-secondary text-lg">
        Core teachings of non-dual philosophy
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- Introduction -->
    <div class="mb-12 bg-bg-white border-l-4 border-accent-saffron p-6 rounded">
      <p class="text-text-primary leading-relaxed">
        Advaita Vedanta is the non-dualistic school of Vedanta philosophy, primarily established by 
        Adi Shankaracharya. It teaches that Brahman (ultimate reality) and Atman (individual self) 
        are identical, and that the perception of duality is due to ignorance (avidya).
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Core Concepts -->
    <div class="space-y-8">
      <!-- 1. The Nature of Reality -->
      <section class="bg-bg-white border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-4">1. The Nature of Reality (Brahman)</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-text-secondary">
          <p>
            <strong class="text-text-primary">Brahman</strong> is the sole reality. It is described as:
          </p>
          <ul class="ml-6 space-y-2">
            <li>• <strong>Sat</strong> (सत्) - Pure Existence, eternal and unchanging</li>
            <li>• <strong>Chit</strong> (चित्) - Pure Consciousness, self-luminous</li>
            <li>• <strong>Ananda</strong> (आनन्द) - Pure Bliss, limitless and complete</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="mt-4">
            Brahman is <em>nirguna</em> (without attributes) and <em>nirvisesha</em> (without distinctions) 
            in its absolute nature, yet appears with attributes (<em>saguna</em>) due to maya.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 2. The Individual Self -->
      <section class="bg-bg-white border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-4">2. The Individual Self (Atman)</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-text-secondary">
          <p>
            <strong class="text-text-primary">Atman</strong> is your true nature, identical with Brahman:
          </p>
          <ul class="ml-6 space-y-2">
            <li>• Not the body, which is gross and perishable</li>
            <li>• Not the mind, which is subtle but still changing</li>
            <li>• Not the intellect, which is an instrument of knowledge</li>
            <li>• Pure consciousness, the witness of all experiences</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="mt-4 bg-bg-sanskrit p-3 rounded italic">
            "That thou art" (Tat Tvam Asi) - The great Upanishadic teaching affirming the identity of Atman and Brahman.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 3. Maya and the World -->
      <section class="bg-bg-white border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-4">3. Maya and the Appearance of the World</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-text-secondary">
          <p>
            <strong class="text-text-primary">Maya</strong> is the mysterious power by which the One appears as many:
          </p>
          <ul class="ml-6 space-y-2">
            <li>• Not absolutely real (sat) like Brahman</li>
            <li>• Not absolutely unreal (asat) like a fantasy</li>
            <li>• Inexplicable (anirvachaniya) - neither existent nor non-existent</li>
            <li>• Has two powers: <em>avarana shakti</em> (veiling) and <em>vikshepa shakti</em> (projecting)</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="mt-4">
            The world is <em>mithya</em> - apparently real but ultimately dependent on Brahman for its existence,
            like a rope appearing as a snake in dim light.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 4. Ignorance and Liberation -->
      <section class="bg-bg-white border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-4">4. Ignorance (Avidya) and Liberation (Moksha)</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-text-secondary">
          <p>
            <strong class="text-text-primary">Avidya</strong> (ignorance) is the root cause of all suffering:
          </p>
          <ul class="ml-6 space-y-2 mb-4">
            <li>• Causes us to identify with the body-mind complex</li>
            <li>• Creates the sense of separation and duality</li>
            <li>• Leads to endless desires and karmic bondage</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong class="text-text-primary">Moksha</strong> (liberation) comes through:
          </p>
          <ul class="ml-6 space-y-2">
            <li>• <strong>Shravana</strong> - Listening to the teachings from a qualified guru</li>
            <li>• <strong>Manana</strong> - Reflecting on the teachings to remove doubts</li>
            <li>• <strong>Nididhyasana</strong> - Deep meditation on the truth</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="mt-4 bg-bg-sanskrit p-3 rounded">
            Liberation is not achieving something new, but recognizing what you already are - 
            pure consciousness, always free, always whole.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 5. The Three States -->
      <section class="bg-bg-white border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-4">5. The Three States of Consciousness</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-text-secondary">
          <p>Every individual experiences three states:</p>
          <ul class="ml-6 space-y-3 mt-3">
            <li>
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Waking (Jagrat)</strong> - 
              Experience of the gross world through senses and mind
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Dream (Swapna)</strong> - 
              Experience of a subtle world created by the mind
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong class="text-text-primary">Deep Sleep (Sushupti)</strong> - 
              State of no experience, where individuality temporarily dissolves
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p class="mt-4">
            <strong class="text-text-primary">Turiya</strong> (the fourth) is not a state but the unchanging 
            consciousness that witnesses all three states - this is your true nature.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- 6. The Path of Knowledge -->
      <section class="bg-bg-white border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-4">6. The Path of Knowledge (Jnana Yoga)</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-text-secondary">
          <p>
            <strong class="text-text-primary">Qualifications</strong> (Sadhana Chatushtaya):
          </p>
          <ul class="ml-6 space-y-2 mb-4">
            <li>• <strong>Viveka</strong> - Discrimination between eternal and non-eternal</li>
            <li>• <strong>Vairagya</strong> - Dispassion towards worldly pleasures</li>
            <li>• <strong>Shatsampat</strong> - Six virtues (control of mind, control of senses, withdrawal, forbearance, faith, concentration)</li>
            <li>• <strong>Mumukshutva</strong> - Intense desire for liberation</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Only a student with these qualifications is fit to receive the direct teaching of Brahman 
            from a qualified guru.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>

    <!-- Important Note -->
    <div class="mt-12 p-6 bg-gradient-to-r from-bg-sanskrit to-bg-white border-2 border-accent-saffron rounded-lg">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-accent-saffron mb-3">⚠️ Essential Reminder</h3>
      <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        These concepts are profound and cannot be fully understood through intellectual study alone. 
        They must be learned in the traditional manner under the guidance of a qualified guru 
        (one who has realized Brahman) in the guru-shishya parampara. Self-study without proper 
        guidance can lead to misunderstanding and confusion.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Navigation -->
    <div class="mt-8 flex justify-center gap-4">
      <a href="/concepts/glossary" class="px-6 py-3 bg-bg-white border-2 border-accent-saffron text-accent-saffron rounded-lg hover:bg-bg-sanskrit transition-colors">
        View Glossary
      </a>
      <a href="/concepts/mahavakyas" class="px-6 py-3 bg-accent-saffron text-white rounded-lg hover:opacity-90 transition-opacity">
        Mahavakyas →
      </a>
    </div>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
